{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}
'''Charles Mackinnon Douglas''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CB|DL|MP}} (2 October 1865 &ndash; 3 February 1924) was a Scottish philosopher, agriculturist and Member of Parliament who represented [[North West Lanarkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North West Lanarkshire]] from 1899 to 1906.<ref name="times">{{cite news |title=Mr. C. M. Douglas |work=[[The Times]] |publisher=The Times Digital Archive |page=12 |date=5 February 1924 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.douglashistory.co.uk/history/charlesmackinnondouglas.htm#.VklavflViko "Charles Mackinnon Douglas"] Douglas Archives. Retrieved 2015-11-15.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ZUmrBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA183 "Staunch Loyalty for the Flag that Stand for Union"] ''Remembering the Past in Nineteenth-Century Scotland''. Retrieved 2015-11-15.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=QmdHAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA178& "Picture-Politics"] ''A Pictorial History of Political Events Connected with South Africa, 1899-1900''. Retrieved 2015-11-15.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=9Ik2OKkJNvsC&pg=RA1-PA99 "Obituary"] ''The Eagle, Volumes 23-24''. Retrieved 2015-11-15.</ref>

==Education and academia==

Douglas was born in Edinburgh, and was educated at [[Edinburgh Academy]], the [[University of Edinburgh]] and the [[University of Freiburg]]. He graduated the University of Edinburgh with first-class honours in philosophy in 1892 and later earned a doctorate from the same institution.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mackinnon|first=Douglas, Charles|date=1892|title=Nature & spirit; the problem of this relation in experience|url=http://hdl.handle.net/1842/24529|language=en}}</ref> He lectured at the university on moral philosophy for seven years. He was the author of studies of English philosopher [[John Stuart Mill]], and co-authored a treatise with Dutch philosopher [[Cornelis Tiele]].<ref name="times"/>

==Career==

He won a seat in Parliament at a by-election in 1899,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=DXdtAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA116 "National(ist) Issues"] ''The 'Local' Irish in the West of Scotland 1851-1921''. Retrieved 2015-11-15.</ref> was re-elected in 1900, but lost in 1906. Unhappy with the Liberal government, he stood unsuccessfully as a Unionist in [[South Lanarkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Lanarkshire]] in December 1910.<ref name="times"/>

During the First World War, he was Chairman of the Lanarkshire [[Territorial Force]] Association. He was made a Companion of the [[Order of the Bath]] in the [[1918 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=30451 |date=1 January 1918 |page=80|supp=y}}</ref><ref name="times"/>

He was chairman of the Scottish Council of Agriculture, chairman of directors of the Highland and Agricultural Society of Scotland and president of the Scottish Agricultural Organization Society and Scottish Chamber of Agriculture.<ref name="times"/> In 1919, he was a member of a [[Royal Commission]] on agriculture in Great Britain.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31463 |date=18 July 1919 |pages=9131–9132 }}</ref>

==Personal life==

In 1895, he married Anne Isabel (''née'' Tod). He died in [[Lesmahagow]] in 1924.<ref name="times"/>

