The '''right to withdraw''' is a concept in [[clinical research ethics]] that a study participant in a [[clinical trial]] has a right to end participation in that trial at will. According to ICH GCP guidelines, a person can withdraw from research at any point of time and it is no binding of participant to reveal the reason of discontinuation.
==Children in research== When children participate in clinical research their parents or guardians must give assent for them to participate, but ethics dictate that even in this case it is best to get the consent of the research subject. Studies have shown that children participating in research have little understanding of the right to withdraw when they are presented with the option.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ondrusek |first1=Nancy |last2=Abramovitch |first2=Rona |last3=Pencharz |first3=Paul |last4=Koren |first4=Gideon |year=1998 |title=Empirical examination of the ability of children to consent to clinical research |journal=Journal of Medical Ethics |volume=24 |issue=3 |pages=158–65 |pmid=9650109 |doi=10.1136/jme.24.3.158 |pmc=1377517}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Edwards |first1=Sarah J.L. |year=2005 |title=Research Participation and the Right to Withdraw |journal=Bioethics |volume=19 |issue=2 |pages=112–30 |pmid=15943021 |doi=10.1111/j.1467-8519.2005.00429.x}}</ref>
==Biobanks== Withdrawal from participating in [[biobank]] research is problematic for many reasons, including the fact that participant's data is often [[de-identification|de-identified]] to grant [[Privacy for research participants|research participant privacy]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Eriksson |first1=Stefan |last2=Helgesson |first2=Gert |year=2005 |title=Potential harms, anonymization, and the right to withdraw consent to biobank research |journal=European Journal of Human Genetics |volume=13 |issue=9 |pages=1071–6 |pmid=15986039 |doi=10.1038/sj.ejhg.5201458}}</ref>
