'''''Studies on Marx and Hegel''''' ({{lang-fr|Études sur Marx et Hegel}}) is a 1955 book about [[Karl Marx]] and [[Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel]] by the French philosopher [[Jean Hyppolite]]. It has received praise from commentators, and has been credited with showing Hegel's anticipation of [[existentialism]].

==Summary==
Hyppolite provides assessments of Hegel's ''[[The Phenomenology of Spirit]]'' (1807), including the significance of Hegel's discussion in that work of the [[French Revolution]]. He also assesses Hegel's ''[[Science of Logic]]'', Marx's ''[[Das Kapital]]'' (1867–1883), and Marx's critique of Hegel's ''[[Elements of the Philosophy of Right]]'' (1820), and discusses [[György Lukács]]'s ''[[The Young Hegel]]'' (1938).{{sfn|Hyppolite|1969|pages=3, 35–69, 70, 94, 169, 126–130}}

==Publication history==
''Studies on Marx and Hegel'' was published by Marcel Rivière et Cie in 1955. In 1969, an English translation by [[John O'Neill (philosopher)|John O'Neill]] was published by [[Heinemann (publisher)|Heinemann Educational Books Ltd]].{{sfn|O'Neill|1969|page=iii}} 

==Reception==
===Academic journals===
''Studies on Marx and Hegel'' received a positive review from Michael Faia in ''[[American Sociological Review]]''.{{sfn|Faia|1970|pages=767–768}} The book was also reviewed by the political scientist [[David McLellan (political scientist)|David McLellan]] in ''[[Sociology (journal)|Sociology]]''.{{sfn|McLellan|1972|page=140}}

Faia credited Hyppolite with helping to clarify Hegel's philosophy, and with showing Marx's indebtedness to [[Charles Darwin]]. He also maintained that Hyppolite showed Hegel's anticipation of the ideas of [[existentialism]].{{sfn|Faia|1970|pages=767–768}}

===Evaluations in books===
The philosopher [[Jean-Paul Sartre]] concluded in ''[[Search for a Method]]'' (1957) Hyppolite was at least partially successful in his attempt to reinterpret Hegel as an existentialist.{{sfn|Sartre|1968|page=9}} Sartre cited ''Studies on Marx and Hegel'' in ''[[Critique of Dialectical Reason]]'' (1960).{{sfn|Sartre|1991|page=308}} The historian [[Peter Gay]] described ''Studies on Marx and Hegel'' as one of the best discussions of [[Marx's theory of alienation|alienation]] in the literature on Marx and Hegel in the second volume of ''The Bourgeois Experience Victoria to Freud'' (1986).{{sfn|Gay|1986|page=458}}

McLellan called ''Studies on Marx and Hegel'' profound in the 1995 edition of his ''[[Karl Marx: His Life and Thought]]''.{{sfn|McLellan|1995|page=442}}

